        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Most of the requirements are similar to the one in the first science goal and we only describe here the differences in requirements.

Sensitivity requirements :

MCFOST calculations predict a flux of 8.14 mJy/beam in the "green beam" at the outer edge of the disc in a 0.08km/s spectral channel in the 12CO J=1-0 transition.
We will increase the signal-to-noise by binning to a 0.4 - 0.5 km/s channel (binning by a factor 5-6). We will thus have a flux of about 50 mJy/beam in such a channel. We therefore ask for a rms of 15mJy/beam.
As for the band 6, the SNR will be much higher than 3 over most the disc surface.

A spectral resolution of 0.5km/s will be sufficient for our study as the the 2-1 transition will be detected at a similar S/N but in a 0.08km/s channel and will allow the accurate mapping of the CO surface. The comparison of the 2 transitions to determine the excitation condition is less demanding in terms of spectral resolution and can be easily performed at a 0.5km/s resolution.

We nevertheless ask for the full resolution of 0.08km/s to avoid smearing due to the keplerien rotation in the central part of the disc where the signal-to-noise will be much higher.



Imaging requirements :

They are the same as for the 1st science goal.
We sample baselines ranging from 20 to 600 klambda in both bands. This corresponds to the C34-5 configuration in band 3.

Correlator setup :

We use a resolution of 0.08km/s for the 12CO 1-0 line and use the remaining basebands for continuum, 6Ghz in order to maximise our sensitivity to the thermal emission large mm grains.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
